tring url, Properties info) throws SQLException {\\n        CONNECT_ATTEMPTS.incrementAndGet();\\n        return null;\\n    }\\n\\n    @Override\\n    public boolean acceptsURL(String url) throws SQLException {\\n        return url.startsWith(\\\"jdbc:jetty-security-test:\\\");\\n    }\\n\\n    @Override\\n    public DriverPropertyInfo[] getPropertyInfo(String url, Properties info) throws SQLException {\\n        return new DriverPropertyInfo[0];\\n    }\\n\\n    @Override\\n    public int getMajorVersion() {\\n        return 1;\\n    }\\n\\n    @Override\\n    public int getMinorVersion() {\\n        return 0;\\n    }\\n\\n    @Override\\n    public boolean jdbcCompliant() {\\n        return false;\\n    }\\n\\n    @Override\\n    public Logger getParentLogger() {\\n        return Logger.getGlobal();\\n    }\\n}\\n\"}\n2587:[recv] {\"type\": \"message_end\", \"message\": {\"role\": \"assistant\", \"content\": [{\"type\": \"thinking\", \"thinking\": \"**Evaluating Git status and tests**\\n\\nI’m looking at the metadata directory and noticing some untracked files. I need to decide if I should avoid committing unrelated changes since they may have been generated by a previous workflow. The user is just testing, so it might be best not to include this metadata. I also want to check if any changes to Jetty_securityTest are necessary. The user mentioned that all top-level test classes are public, but I'm wondering if I should remove the placeholder instead.\\n\\n**Evaluating naming conventions**\\n\\nI need to check the reflect-config with the `$` in JSON. I'm contemplating whether having a static nested class name with a `$` violates the rule against using `$` in test class or file names. This isn't a test class but a nested class called \\\"JDBCLoginServiceTest$TestDriver.\\\" While it's not a helper, I recognize that it could confuse the naming conventions. I wonder if I should define a top-level non-public class to avoid the `$` issue while also adhering to the guidelines.\\n\\n**Understanding class accessibility**\\n\\nI'm grappling with whether a package-private class can be instantiated reflectively. It seems that `Class.newInstance()` can only work with public classes and their nullary constructors, which means I could face issues with IllegalAccessException for package-private classes. Since I can't have two public top-level classes in one file, it looks like using a nested public class is my only option without creating an extra file. But I'm concerned about whether that would conflict with the one-to-one mapping rule for generated test files.\\n\\n**Considering class imports**\\n\\nI'm thinking about the task of removing nested class imports. It seems like a good idea to simplify the code by cleaning it up. This could make the code more readable and maintainable. Also, it's a good practice to reduce complexity when possible. Hmm, let me ensure the changes don't disrupt functionality. I'll approach this carefully to make sure it stays user-friendly while effectively streamlining the code. Let's proceed cautiously!\", \"thinkingSignature\": \"{\\\"id\\\":\\\"rs_0b1785793cebabb60169f383931cbc81a08e06e5433a72d5f3\\\",\\\"type\\\":\\\"reasoning\\\",\\\"encrypted_content\\\":\\\"gAAAAABp84Og-_-uzTj64xH83x3ICuGxb9Fi8KakGj505Qg4nyDFoWewGPKEXvG_X-tAtS9RcmApXLqDyiGjJY2Cbg8WVYfigyQ_6AmdU1U_nDcr74SR-S01a4zpxj7_Rb9dN1yfwF0r0E4oQNCh50i4dbHgYy8Ms1j0u4VsYsB77k7N3pPmR917Y9em6ABdenOH3hTU0RQ7Rt4ccBF6ynqjRt_mYuzILViPJwoWMs9UsWU3Y_g-vU3zMAIdpWiMcQ_LjXD6F4-oCY3nk_iP4I5d8al_wpPjY8vD8sIFUNvR8AQ8tWJQ3FyM2865p3z0oSe2gZbrDC6dkHVfbvaD9B1iCuG2mt3G0sZNSlj0Bu92rttXbUZ0ELIhIqcW2-lnCI0k-9vI_iECsM6xo_NvFsNoeVXQXS7FR0ONs6DssWQXNWPgjBkEvEwPQ0A8OlhJ4Prbbn8GbFeBpxRTZz23eBV1MW7JUQ36MSIi3ycno4OqoRpW6y_pwAtBRb3L7oYVkVvT0_VP1l0srRyu5j6BfqY-lmEyL9dZinnRvoAFdCLNMz3ujRdyZgcchTHxbLT1OAObGk1xtTyavvOECr4U02GXs2tHcjtbA1KTfb3_bQzTm7ulTyBsTS9yQBboh_v4EJt4t10IgI5ehZcjMCsfo_6k-STdlajraxI0HMvCINDzC-dVBahGVLxsfwKkcLRSfYi3IIqRlBMrq5l1UY4QNRv4SoaTrD79438QuxXNEWBOrwzLIVY2NilWT