ary\\\":[{\\\"type\\\":\\\"summary_text\\\",\\\"text\\\":\\\"**Evaluating Git status and tests**\\\\n\\\\nI’m looking at the metadata directory and noticing some untracked files. I need to decide if I should avoid committing unrelated changes since they may have been generated by a previous workflow. The user is just testing, so it might be best not to include this metadata. I also want to check if any changes to Jetty_securityTest are necessary. The user mentioned that all top-level test classes are public, but I'm wondering if I should remove the placeholder instead.\\\"},{\\\"type\\\":\\\"summary_text\\\",\\\"text\\\":\\\"**Evaluating naming conventions**\\\\n\\\\nI need to check the reflect-config with the `$` in JSON. I'm contemplating whether having a static nested class name with a `$` violates the rule against using `$` in test class or file names. This isn't a test class but a nested class called \\\\\\\"JDBCLoginServiceTest$TestDriver.\\\\\\\" While it's not a helper, I recognize that it could confuse the naming conventions. I wonder if I should define a top-level non-public class to avoid the `$` issue while also adhering to the guidelines.\\\"},{\\\"type\\\":\\\"summary_text\\\",\\\"text\\\":\\\"**Understanding class accessibility**\\\\n\\\\nI'm grappling with whether a package-private class can be instantiated reflectively. It seems that `Class.newInstance()` can only work with public classes and their nullary constructors, which means I could face issues with IllegalAccessException for package-private classes. Since I can't have two public top-level classes in one file, it looks like using a nested public class is my only option without creating an extra file. But I'm concerned about whether that would conflict with the one-to-one mapping rule for generated test files.\\\"},{\\\"type\\\":\\\"summary_text\\\",\\\"text\\\":\\\"**Considering class imports**\\\\n\\\\nI'm thinking about the task of removing nested class imports. It seems like a good idea to